===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|masoun}}, {{m|enm|machun}}, from {{etyl|xno|en}} {{m|fro|machun}}, {{m|fro|masson}}, from Old Low {{etyl|frk|en}} *{{m|frk||mattio}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*maitô}} (compare German obsolete {{m|de|Metz}}, Stein{{m|de|Steinmetz|metz}}), from {{m|gem-pro|*maitaną||to cut, hew}} (compare Old High German {{m|goh|meizan}}, East Frisian {{m|stq|matje}}, Old Norse {{m|non|meita}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*mai-d-||to alter}} (compare Old Lithuanian ap{{m|lt|apmaitinti|maitinti|to wound}}, Latvian {{m|lv|maitat|màitât|to spoil, destroy}}), enlargement of {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*mei-||to change, exchange}}. More at {{l|en|mean}}, {{l|en|mutate}}.

